      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is a valid interpretive method that respects the intentions of the Founding Fathers, but it can be criticized for its reliance on historical interpretation, which is inherently subjective. Critics argue that this subjectivity can lead to arbitrary outcomes, as different scholars may interpret the same historical evidence in various ways. However, originalists counter that their approach provides a consistent framework for constitutional interpretation, preventing judges from imposing their own values on the law. Ultimately, the debate between originalism and other interpretive methods reflects differing views on the role of judges and the Constitution in society.",
